                <h1>The Yellow Wallpaper: Exploring the Role of the Husband</h1>
                <p>In Charlotte Perkins Gilman's "The Yellow Wallpaper," the protagonist's husband, John, embodies the oppressive patriarchy of the late 19th century. He dismisses her mental illness as mere hysteria, enforcing a treatment that limits her freedom. His controlling nature both isolates her and intensifies her descent into madness, symbolized by the wallpaper itself.</p>
